text:
my periods are like a beautiful song on loop.
beautiful songs are usually painful,
but they make you feel secure, they make you feel tranquil.
their sole actuality makes you feel serene.
just the fact that my periods are alive provides me safety, it gives me the sense of pride.
it flows in a rhythm making me pure,
the only barren space which is filled with respect.
the battery dies and the song pauses,
but i keep humming it in my mind, to cherish it till the time i hear the music again, till the time i perfectly learn to hit the high notes.
.
.
©i.v. @poembryo .
--------×--------
.

don't you feel the same?

text_retweet:
prostitution was legalised in victoria australia in 1994.  in that time illegal brothel numbers have increased 500% and those women engaged in legal ‘sex-work’ are more often than not, in highly coercive situations.  men who use women do absolutely nothing to ensure that the women they use are not being coerced.  if you are being coerced, you cannot give consent and men know this.  the nordic model offers an asymmetrical approach when the people criminalised are the people driving the demand: the pimps and johns, whom are mostly men. #endsexualslavery #enddemand #antiporn #antipimp #antijohn #nordicmodelnow #feminism #radical #occupiedaustralia #repost @nordicmodelnow ・・・
did you know, women often struggle to leave prostitution?

most of the time, women continue in prostitution because of an absence of viable alternatives. common factors that make it hard to leave include: having no training or qualifications, being dependent on drugs or alcohol, being coerced by a “boyfriend” or pimp, having debts, and a criminal record.

read more: https://nordicmodelnow.org/facts-about-prostitution/fact-women-often-struggle-to-leave-prostitution/

most of the time, women continue in prostitution because of an absence of viable alternatives. common factors that make it hard to leave include: having no training or qualifications, being dependent on drugs or alcohol, being coerced by a “boyfriend” or pimp, having debts, and a criminal record.

read more: https://nordicmodelnow.org/facts-about-prostitution/fact-women-often-struggle-to-leave-prostitution/

text:
#mirácómonosponemos.

thelma fardín, actriz argentina, se ha atrevido a contar su historia, apoyada, respaldada y abrazada por el colectivo de actrices argentinas. han sido varias las compañeras que han señalado a juan darthés, un artista local, por abusos sexuales. esta vez thelma ha confesado que fue violada por él a los 16 años, en una de las giras de la novela "patito feo". "mirá cómo me ponés", cuenta thelma que dijo juan antes de comenzar a violarla.

el colectivo ha hecho viral el video y abierto el debate en redes sociales a través de la etiqueta #mirácómonosponemos.

tras la repercusión que tomó su denuncia, otras dos actrices apuntaron contra darthés: ana coacci y natalia juncos, por experiencias similares en 1998 y 2005.

no nos vamos a seguir callando,
machirulo,
escóndete.

hermana,
estamos contigo. 🔥 🔥 🔥

vean el enlace entero en la bio 🙏
.
 #noesno #sororidad #bastaya #metoo #machiruloescondete @soythelmafardin @actrices.argentinas #estamosconustedes #juntassomosmásfuertes #difusión #nuncamássolxs

text:
チョ・ナムジュ 著／斎藤 真理子 訳
『82年生まれ、キム・ジヨン』（筑摩書房）

読み始めてすぐ、胸が詰まる。

淡々と綴られる33歳の女性の半生が、社会に潜む不平等をあぶり出す。女性に生まれただけで直面する困難は、これほどまでなのか。

挫折、疲労、恐怖感。
人生に立ちはだかるもの。

大げさではない、これが現実。
でもまだ変えられる。

【物化女性vs身體自主？】#wyk9up

呢啲terms近年開始由學術象牙塔，滲到出去比大眾認識到，絕對係好事。但同時，由於呢啲概念本來就有好多詮釋嘅方向，所以成日會被利用、濫用或曲解。更甚，不少群眾剛認識到呢啲字，就只係想攞啲字黎鬧人，而唔係講道理，會抽空曬背景黎講。有見及此，我都想講下我對呢啲concept 嘅見解。

____________ 
喺女性主義嘅脈絡中（特別是基進女性主義radical feminism），「物化」往往聚焦於對女性身體嘅物化，背後脈絡為批判剝削、支配女性嘅父權社會。

____________

所謂父權社會，姐係性別二元、性別定型強烈、男尊女卑嘅刻板社會，女性最大嘅存在價值就係被洩慾同生育，除此之外都係負累。其實，只係半世紀前，我媽媽嗰輩，都已經會有大部分人認為女孩子唔應該讀書；直到社會政策帶頭改變風氣(例如推全民免費教育)，幾十年後嘅今日，香港社會制度上先大致上性別平等（我認為）。但思想上，仍然會有人認為女性天生智慧較遜、唔洗識咁多野，亦仍有人認為男性應當獨力擔起成頭家、流血不流淚等。

____________

男主外、女主內呢個觀念就係父權社會其中一個軸心思想，喺呢個基礎上，無論制度、抑或文化，男性都會喺公共領域獲得優勢。因此，統治階層、上位者多為男性。偶爾或許會出現女性領導者，但稱謂通常都要加上個「女」字，惟恐天下不知女性做領導者係幾咁例外。

____________

喺父權社會下，女性被預設係沒有權力，沒有公共地位的，女性嘅思想或需要都係不被重視嘅。因此，「物化」很惡，因為女性本身就是被剝削的，假如還要比男性搓圓撳扁，視為物件去看待或利用，又往往不能收穫這些被利用嘅成果 ，亦無途徑、無資源為自己真正嘅想法發聲，當然「物化」係好有問題嘅事。 
____________

但今日嘅香港，係咪真係再好似以往咁，女性從制度上、資源上就係被男性剝削住，又欠缺發聲嘅媒介或途徑呢？我並不認為係咁的。 我認為，現今社會仍然有針對性別嘅差別待遇或歧視，但係係各有各歧視，而唔係女性單方面被害和被剝削，男性同其他性別，都同樣要面對佢地嘅性別差別待遇，而且可能不比女性面對嘅嚴峻。香港社會主要嘅權力問題，可能係來自階層同錢，而唔係性別。

____________

亦因此，即使係「物化女性」，亦變得無以前咁惡咁差，因為女性作為一整個群體，不再係無權利、無權力、無平台。雖然思想上古板嘅人仍有不少，但時移勢易，女性要喺公共領域、職場上發揮，都似乎無以前咁困難重重。改善空間當然仍有，例如研究增加侍產假、提供母乳友善嘅辦公環境、彈性工時等，都能夠進一步釋放女性嘅工作潛能。 
____________ 
喺呢個背景下，我會認為追求自主、推廣自主，係比較能夠突破社會喺思想、文化上對各種性別嘅剩餘「框框」。既然女性已經唔再係無權無勢，咁當佢地嘅身體被當成商品、慾望載體之時，亦唔應該即時覺得佢係被「物化」，而係要睇下佢有無同意呢種行為。假如佢係同意被當成商品看待，就不存在以往性別不平等下嘅什麼物化不物化。

____________

將自己「物化」、「商品化」有好多形式，例如澳洲呢位醫生，喜歡將自己身體當作畫布黎紋身，力排眾議都要繼續實行自己嘅喜好。由醫生嘅例子可見，自主、力排眾議，好多時都要睇條件看本錢。網上不少支持醫生嘅言論，都係基於佢嘅能力同紋身好睇。假如佢只係一個低下階層，應該都會被紋身嘅刻板印象擊倒吧，而當遭反對，亦無咁多人力物力財力對抗吧。@rosesarered_23

____________

又有人會話，點解永遠都係啲奇怪嘅人先會主張身體自主之類。雖然係諗唔通但又無講錯：自由、自主呢啲概念嘅可貴之處，正正係在於佢地要用黎保護一啲脆弱、不被接納嘅嘢。假如你嘅思想愛惡，完全符合社會主流期望，那很好，你本來就已經有很大自由同空間做你喜歡嘅事，比如穿長褲、比如留短髮、比如行山，呢啲嘢你做嘅時候，視乎你嘅背景，一般都不會惹來好大阻撓。 點解某啲人要強調自主自由嘅重要性，恰恰就係因為佢地平日得不到發揮嘅空間，而之所以沒有空間，就係因為不符合大眾要求，所以被排斥吧。恭喜你係大多數人，你可以繼續你嘅生活，但請也嘗試尊重與你不同的人的生活方式吧。

____________

參考文章: 《動漫萌角色：動漫文化物化了女性？》王佩迪

stop_filter_tweet: - 【物化女性vs身體自主？】yk9up 呢啲terms近年開始由學術象牙塔，滲到出去比大眾認識到，絕對係好事。但同時，由於呢啲概念本來就有好多詮釋嘅方向，所以成日會被利用、濫用或曲解。更甚，不少群眾剛認識到呢啲字，就只係想攞啲字黎鬧人，而唔係講道理，會抽空曬背景黎講。有見及此，我都想講下我對呢啲concept 嘅見解。 ____________ 喺女性主義嘅脈絡中（特別是基進女性主義radical feminism），「物化」往往聚焦於對女性身體嘅物化，背後脈絡為批判剝削、支配女性嘅父權社會。 ____________ 所謂父權社會，姐係性別二元、性別定型強烈、男尊女卑嘅刻板社會，女性最大嘅存在價值就係被洩慾同生育，除此之外都係負累。其實，只係半世紀前，我媽媽嗰輩，都已經會有大部分人認為女孩子唔應該讀書；直到社會政策帶頭改變風氣 ( 例如推全民免費教育 ) ，幾十年後嘅今日，香港社會制度上先大致上性別平等（我認為）。但思想上，仍然會有人認為女性天生智慧較遜、唔洗識咁多野，亦仍有人認為男性應當獨力擔起成頭家、流血不流淚等。 ____________ 男主外、女主內呢個觀念就係父權社會其中一個軸心思想，喺呢個基礎上，無論制度、抑或文化，男性都會喺公共領域獲得優勢。因此，統治階層、上位者多為男性。偶爾或許會出現女性領導者，但稱謂通常都要加上個「女」字，惟恐天下不知女性做領導者係幾咁例外。 ____________ 喺父權社會下，女性被預設係沒有權力，沒有公共地位的，女性嘅思想或需要都係不被重視嘅。因此，「物化」很惡，因為女性本身就是被剝削的，假如還要比男性搓圓撳扁，視為物件去看待或利用，又往往不能收穫這些被利用嘅成果 ，亦無途徑、無資源為自己真正嘅想法發聲，當然「物化」係好有問題嘅事。 ____________ 但今日嘅香港，係咪真係再好似以往咁，女性從制度上、資源上就係被男性剝削住，又欠缺發聲嘅媒介或途徑呢？我並不認為係咁的。 我認為，現今社會仍然有針對性別嘅差別待遇或歧視，但係係各有各歧視，而唔係女性單方面被害和被剝削，男性同其他性別，都同樣要面對佢地嘅性別差別待遇，而且可能不比女性面對嘅嚴峻。香港社會主要嘅權力問題，可能係來自階層同錢，而唔係性別。 ____________ 亦因此，即使係「物化女性」，亦變得無以前咁惡咁差，因為女性作為一整個群體，不再係無權利、無權力、無平台。雖然思想上古板嘅人仍有不少，但時移勢易，女性要喺公共領域、職場上發揮，都似乎無以前咁困難重重。改善空間當然仍有，例如研究增加侍產假、提供母乳友善嘅辦公環境、彈性工時等，都能夠進一步釋放女性嘅工作潛能。 ____________ 喺呢個背景下，我會認為追求自主、推廣自主，係比較能夠突破社會喺思想、文化上對各種性別嘅剩餘「框框」。既然女性已經唔再係無權無勢，咁當佢地嘅身體被當成商品、慾望載體之時，亦唔應該即時覺得佢係被「物化」，而係要睇下佢有無同意呢種行為。假如佢係同意被當成商品看待，就不存在以往性別不平等下嘅什麼物化不物化。 ____________ 將自己「物化」、「商品化」有好多形式，例如澳洲呢位醫生，喜歡將自己身體當作畫布黎紋身，力排眾議都要繼續實行自己嘅喜好。由醫生嘅例子可見，自主、力排眾議，好多時都要睇條件看本錢。網上不少支持醫生嘅言論，都係基於佢嘅能力同紋身好睇。假如佢只係一個低下階層，應該都會被紋身嘅刻板印象擊倒吧，而當遭反對，亦無咁多人力物力財力對抗吧。osesarered_23 ____________ 又有人會話，點解永遠都係啲奇怪嘅人先會主張身體自主之類。雖然係諗唔通但又無講錯：自由、自主呢啲概念嘅可貴之處，正正係在於佢地要用黎保護一啲脆弱、不被接納嘅嘢。假如你嘅思想愛惡，完全符合社會主流期望，那很好，你本來就已經有很大自由同空間做你喜歡嘅事，比如穿長褲、比如留短髮、比如行山，呢啲嘢你做嘅時候，視乎你嘅背景，一般都不會惹來好大阻撓。 點解某啲人要強調自主自由嘅重要性，恰恰就係因為佢地平日得不到發揮嘅空間，而之所以沒有空間，就係因為不符合大眾要求，所以被排斥吧。恭喜你係大多數人，你可以繼續你嘅生活，但請也嘗試尊重與你不同的人的生活方式吧。 ____________ 參考文章 : 《動漫萌角色：動漫文化物化了女性？》王佩迪

text:
"terça - feira na academia durante um treino, perguntei ao rapaz que estava usando o aparelho quantas séries faltavam para ele terminar o exercício, ele respondeu que faltava 1 e disse que eu poderia revezar, eu respondi dizendo que ele poderia terminar que eu esperaria, ele insistiu dizendo que eu poderia usar o aparelho antes dele varias vezes ( sendo que faltava apenas uma série para ele ), depois de eu ter negado e insistido dizendo que ele poderia terminar ele concluiu a série e ficou ao lado do aparelho esperando eu começar, fingi que estava fazendo uma ligação e me afastei um pouco dele, ele só saiu do lado do aparelho depois que percebeu que eu estava falando no telefone. nossa, me senti como se eu fosse um objeto pra aquele cara, desde a primeira vez que fiz a pergunta a ele, senti o olhar sobre mim e senti nojo dele na mesma hora. depois percebi que ele ficava olhando pra outras mulheres treinando também. nunca tinha passado por situações como essa dentro da academia e foi horrível!" .
relato de camila oliveira, 17 anos, jequié/bahia.
.

text:
🌈
شبکه‌ی "من و تو" همجنس‌گراستیز از آب در آمد!

سریال ویکتوریا هفته‌هاست که در شبکه‌ی من و تو در حال پخش است. در نسخه‌ی اصلی این سریال که از شبکه‌ی itv انگلیس پخش شده است در فصل دوم قسمت هفتم بوسه‌ای بین دو شخصیت سریال (لرد دروموند؛ رئیس دفتر نخست وزیر و لرد آلفرد رئیس دفتر ملکه ویکتوریا) به وقوع می‌پیوندد. این بوسه که بسیاری از رسانه‌های داخلی انگلستان را تحت تاثیر خود قراد داد و با جستجویی در فضای مجازی از یوتیوب تا سرچ ساده در گوگل براحتی می‌توانید نسخه‌های مختلفی از اخبار و فیلم‌های مربوط به این بخش از سریال و سلسله اتفاقات بین این دو فرد که منجر به این صحنه‌ی عاشقانه گردید را مشاهده کنید.
شبکه‌ی من و تو در اقدامی همجنس‌گراستیزانه و برخلاف شعار ابتدایی این شبکه مبنی بر "برای همه‌ی گرایش‌های جنسی"صحنه‌ی بوسه‌ی این دو را سانسور کرد! این در حالیست که هیچ‌ یک از صحنه‌های بوسه‌ی بین دگرجنس‌گرایان در این تلویزیون و در این سریال تاکنون سانسور نشده است. آیا شبکه‌ی من و تو نباید پاسخگوی این اقدام شنیع خود باشد؟؟؟ آیا این آزادی بیانیست که شبکه‌ی من و تو مدعی آن است؟!
@manotoofficial
#lgbt #gay #gaypride #metoo #dayinlgbtq #lgbtq
#همجنسگرا #گی

text:
🌟kriminalinekalendern lucka 15🌟 swipa!➡️ ☠dagens micronovell grundar sig i rädslan för hur världen kommer att se ut när mina döttrar bli större. ska de gå igenom samma skit som vi? tro att ballaballa är ett tecken på uppskattning, och att gå med på sex leder till kärlek? att deras kropp inte duger om inte killarna i korridoren betygsätter den högt? att det är deras fel att andra är idioter?
🎀det har hänt så mycket bara på något år... alla samtal. allt som fått komma ut. ärligheten, inte minst mot oss själva. allt fint och viktigt som t.ex @miaskaringerlazar och @stinawollter sprider. alla nya tankar och idéer.
👭jag hoppas att vi som föräldrar lyckas med vårt uppdrag att uppfostra trygga, starka, välinformerade individer och att vi alla uppfostrat världen ännu mer by then.
annars jävlar👊🏻

did you know, women often struggle to leave prostitution?

most of the time, women continue in prostitution because of an absence of viable alternatives. common factors that make it hard to leave include: having no training or qualifications, being dependent on drugs or alcohol, being coerced by a “boyfriend” or pimp, having debts, and a criminal record.

text:
прямо с утра прочла статью о дискриминации женщин при приеме на работу в рф по причине того, что они могут уйти в декрет. я даже не буду обсуждать, что государство платит эти декретные деньги, а не работодатель. просто проедем это.
короче, опять вскипело у меня. опять бомбит! вспоминаю весь холивар связанный с компанией #metoo и как наши журналисты писали блядские статьи про «сами виноваты» и что феминизм - это говно и не нужное в развитых странах, так как у нас с этим все ок. и если ты феминистка, то иди и таскай шпалы. боже, как можно не понимать, что феминизм - это не добровольный выбор? как можно думать, что даже в развитых странах не ущемляют женщин и не подвергают домогательствам? вот, когда пишут, что раз изнасиловали, то ты сама виновата - это, блять, что? не сексизм? 
не оправдание насильника? 
и при чем тут шпалы? женщина борется не за то, чтобы шпалы с мужиком на равне таскать, а чтобы он ее за низший сорт не считал. от того, что бабы шпалы таскают, никто еще их не признал равными мужикам. обычно наоборот, сама что-то сделаешь и все сразу такие: «мужика бы тебе!» сама разберусь кого мне нужно. мне нужно к моему ротвейлеру только французского бульдога! кстати, и многие из мужчин нынче шпалы таскают? да что тут рассуждать? если вы #сексист, если вы страдаете мизогонией, то нам не по пути. и если вы #гомофоб и #ватник, то вам туда же. 
и еще, вот это вот: «женщина должна быть женщиной», «женщина должна быть за мужчиной», «женщина должна быть нежной» что вообще значит «нежной» «быть женщиной»? 😂я вот женщина и не понимаю о чем речь. бля...просто идите и отдайте свои кредиты, которые вы должны за ваш телевизор. это я вам как женщина говорю, указывающая на утопленного мужика на фото, который тоже говорил, что я ему что-то там должна. не видите утопленника? а он там есть! 
#feminism #girlpower #дискриминацияженщин #феминизм

stop_filter_tweet: прямо с утра прочла статью о дискриминации женщин при приеме на работу в рф по причине того , что они могут уйти в декрет . я даже не буду обсуждать , что государство платит эти декретные деньги , а не работодатель . просто проедем это . короче , опять вскипело у меня . опять бомбит ! вспоминаю весь холивар связанный с компанией и как наши журналисты писали блядские статьи про « сами виноваты » и что феминизм - это говно и не нужное в развитых странах , так как у нас с этим все ок . и если ты феминистка , то иди и таскай шпалы . боже , как можно не понимать , что феминизм - это не добровольный выбор ? как можно думать , что даже в развитых странах не ущемляют женщин и не подвергают домогательствам ? вот , когда пишут , что раз изнасиловали , то ты сама виновата - это , блять , что ? не сексизм ? не оправдание насильника ? и при чем тут шпалы ? женщина борется не за то , чтобы шпалы с мужиком на равне таскать , а чтобы он ее за низший сорт не считал . от того , что бабы шпалы таскают , никто еще их не признал равными мужикам . обычно наоборот , сама что-то сделаешь и все сразу такие : « мужика бы тебе ! » сама разберусь кого мне нужно . мне нужно к моему ротвейлеру только французского бульдога ! кстати , и многие из мужчин нынче шпалы таскают ? да что тут рассуждать ? если вы если вы страдаете мизогонией , то нам не по пути . и если вы и то вам туда же . и еще , вот это вот : « женщина должна быть женщиной » , « женщина должна быть за мужчиной » , « женщина должна быть нежной » что вообще значит « нежной » « быть женщиной » ? 😂я вот женщина и не понимаю о чем речь . бля ... просто идите и отдайте свои кредиты , которые вы должны за ваш телевизор . это я вам как женщина говорю , указывающая на утопленного мужика на фото , который тоже говорил , что я ему что-то там должна . не видите утопленника ? а он там есть !

text:
this is the witness statement by a uyghur #muslim sister on the torture and abuse she went through inside china's concentration camps. in her full story she talks about how she was arrested multiple times and spent 10 months inside the camps. her kids were taken away from her and once she was released she found out one of her children had died and she was reunited with the other 2. she talks about how she was stripped naked and put in some computerised machine after which then she was dressed in uniform like that of prisoners. she was one one occasion interrogated for 4 days and night and though that she had seizures and loss on consciousness.  they were forced to memorize and recite songs every morning praising #china and it's leader. they were forced to take certain pills and drink some typa liquid which led to loss of menstruation, bleeding, and even death for sone. in her cell there were about 60 people. when they had to sleep 15 people would stand up and the rest would sleep sideways and they would rotate every few hours. and her torture in the tiger chair is mentioned in the above video. she witnessed 9 deaths in her cell in 3 months.
.
in 2018, in the 21st century this is still happening and the world is silent. forget putting a stop to it, no one is even really investigating these crimes. and the few reporters that do go to the province are stopped from recording the camps by chinese police. what do they have to hide if it's just "education camps"?
.
also one thing i don't like is people shouting 'fake news' like #trump to anything that they dont know about. the united nations have spoken about this, china has spoken about the existence of these camps, you have hundreds maybe thousands of people who've given witness statements regarding themselves or their family members who are in these camps, you have #uyghur #muslims who speak about living conditions inside the province. and you tell me every single one of them is lying? stop with the ignorance and go do your research and get some knowledge. share and let the world know what is happening. #islam #quran

this is the witness statement by a uyghur #muslim sister on the torture and abuse she went through inside china's concentration camps. in her full story she talks about how she was arrested multiple times and spent 10 months inside the camps. her kids were taken away from her and once she was released she found out one of her children had died and she was reunited with the other 2. she talks about how she was stripped naked and put in some computerised machine after which then she was dressed in uniform like that of prisoners. she was one one occasion interrogated for 4 days and night and though that she had seizures and loss on consciousness.  they were forced to memorize and recite songs every morning praising #china and it is leader. they were forced to take certain pills and drink some typa liquid which led to loss of menstruation, bleeding, and even death for sone. in her cell there were about 60 people. when they had to sleep 15 people would stand up and the rest would sleep sideways and they would rotate every few hours. and her torture in the tiger chair is mentioned in the above video. she witnessed 9 deaths in her cell in 3 months.
.
in 2018, in the 21st century this is still happening and the world is silent. forget putting a stop to it, no one is even really investigating these crimes. and the few reporters that do go to the province are stopped from recording the camps by chinese police. what do they have to hide if it is just "education camps"?
.

_________________________________

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
menjelang awal tahun 2019 saat sebuah perhelatan perfilman besar bernama academy awards akan diadakan, steve mcqueen kembali menunjukkan keistimewaannya sebagai sutradara dengan "craft" yang luar biasa lewat #widows. berkisah tentang tiga orang janda yang harus melakukan perampokan akibat ditinggal mati suami-suami mereka dengan hutang yang luar biasa besarnya, steve mcqueen mengambil pendekatan kombinasi drama politik dengan heist-thriller untuk menunjukkan kekuatan para wanita independen yang sudah jengah dengan ketidakadilan yang mereka dapatkan dari tokoh-tokoh pria brengsek di sekitar mereka. hasilnya? bombastis, dramatis, menegangkan, dan padat akan pesan.

widows memberikan salah satu penampilan ensemble cast terbaik di tahun ini lewat performa viola davis, michelle rodriguez, dan elizabeth debicki. mereka mempunyai dinamika yang unik. masing-masing berbeda ras, latar belakang, dan tabiat, namun dipersatukan oleh keadaan. mcqueen sabar dan telaten memanfaatkan pengembangan sub-plot di film ini untuk menaikkan intensitas ketegangan sekaligus eksposisi "what's at stake here." gillian flynn yang ikut bekerjasama dalam menulis dan merancang cerita serta penuturannya turut memberikan sentuhan khasnya berupa "plot twist" yang tidak hanya gelap, namun relevan dalam melawan narasi "not all men" yang semakin menjadi-jadi di tengah kampanye #metoo ini. sebagai seorang aktor, daniel kaluuya memberikan salah satu akting terbaiknya lewat karakter jatemme, seorang hitman bengis yang selalu mencoba untuk "bersenang-senang" dalam menyelesaikan tugasnya. namun sebagai sebuah karakter, relevansi keberadaan jatemme begitu lemah, seakan-akan ditulis hanya untuk menominasikan daniel kaluuya di ajang best supporting actor di academy awards tahun depan.

text:
at a hearing before the senate judiciary committee, christopher wylie described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters. the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like ‘drain the swamp’ or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the ‘deep state’ that weren’t necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement.

jon sharman

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

text:
tonight i am simply in awe of the way god moves.🖤 i ask daily for divine connections, and he continually delivers that to me. 
god is so faithful and good. 
and 
as ugly as my life has been over the last decade, i am so grateful for it. 
i am grateful for the trials that have caused me to fall on my knees, because it has taught me to praise before my breakthrough. 
it has taught me to fully trust god instead of myself. 
it has taught me to allow him to fight my battles. 
it has given me strength.
it has molded me into who i am today. 
it has lead me to the most beautiful relationships i could have ever asked for. •
what satan meant for evil, god has turned into good. •
sometimes you go through ugly stuff, in order to become who you were called to be and fully walk in your purpose. *************************
embrace the struggle and look at it as your greatest opportunity for growth, blessings, peace, joy, freedom and abundance. •
god is bigger than that mountain you are facing. 
don’t lose hope. 
fight on your knees.
praise him before the breakthrough. 
put yourself in the right places to find the right people. 
and trust all of this will be used for your good, as you continually surrender the circumstances over to him. 
xo 🖤

text:
опережая закат в поисках рапы... #листай ☀️🌞🌙🌘🌝🌜🌛
_
на эльтоне тебя не покидает ощущение, что ты находишься на другой планете, и это действительно так, тут всё необычно.
_
озеро представляет собой огромнейшую котловину, дно которой покрыто сплошным плотным слоем постоянно выпадающей из раствора соли - называется этот слой "новосадок". слои новосадка благодаря внешним физическим факторам чередуются с прослойками грязи, опоясывающей широкой полосой всё озеро. под слоем новосадка залегают мощные отложения соли. а непосредственный самый верхний жидкий слой соляного озера носит название - "рапа" - высококонцентрированный раствор соли. но эльтон это не только рапа, но и целебные грязи, свойства которой просто уникальны. эльтонские грязи по своему составу относятся к высокосолевым иловым сульфидным и представляют собой однородную массу довольно плотной консистенции, долго удерживающую тепло, с запахом сероводорода. эльтонская грязь - единственная в мире по составу и лечебным свойствам аналогичная грязи мёртвого моря, но превосходящая по содержанию сульфидов и органических веществ, экологичности и соотвественно эффективности. эффект принятия этой грязи впечатляет.
_

_

озеро представляет собой огромнейшую котловину, дно которой покрыто сплошным плотным слоем постоянно выпадающей из раствора соли - называется этот слой "новосадок". слои новосадка благодаря внешним физическим факторам чередуются с прослойками грязи, опоясывающей широкой полосой всё озеро. под слоем новосадка залегают мощные отложения соли. а непосредственный самый верхний жидкий слой соляного озера носит название - "рапа" - высококонцентрированный раствор соли. но эльтон это не только рапа, но и целебные грязи, свойства которой просто уникальны. эльтонские грязи по своему составу относятся к высокосолевым иловым сульфидным и представляют собой однородную массу довольно плотной консистенции, долго удерживающую тепло, с запахом сероводорода. эльтонская грязь - единственная в мире по составу и лечебным свойствам аналогичная грязи мёртвого моря, но превосходящая по содержанию сульфидов и органических веществ, экологичности и соотвественно эффективности. эффект принятия этой грязи впечатляет.

сотрудники социальной сети instagram проанализировали поставленные пользователями смайлики, геолокации и хештеги и опубликовали итоги 2018 года. об этом сообщается на официальном сайте instagram. 
таким образом, самой счастливой геолокацией instagram признал диснейленд в токио, так как больше всего счастливых смайликов в 2018 году пользователи ставили именно под фотографиями из японского диснейленда. 
также эксперты назвали самый популярный фильтр для лица: им стал фильтр с сердечками на глазах. а, например, самыми часто используемыми хештегами в 2018 году были #metoo, #timesup и #marchforourlives.

text: i’m represented by amy luker @lukeragency and she trawls through a lot of the bs #casting calls- that are hollywood at its most stereotypical, dated & offensive- and pulls out the very few that acknowledge gender/identity/sex reality & science of 2018 (usually being cast by @mrrpmurphy 😂.. god bless him). i look @breakdownservices myself everyday and although i’m able to register with them and @castingnetworks as #nonbinary & am open to playing cis women & men,  i can’t specify #intersex (old word #hermaphrodite) in my profile- cause although we are as common as red hair & green eyes.. 1 in 1500 births.. we don’t fucking *exist in the media 🌎 yet... so like all non-binary people i have to put up with the near total invisibility for our gender- and strict men/women division- and the ridiculous, old-fashioned gendering of roles that is the norm. this one particularly gets my goat tonight- my dentist @drbaseri used me in his ad as i have the million $s smile.. but for this casting i have to ‘bring my own dress’!! fuck off with your gender tyranny. i’m so sick of this shit.. even liberals who are reacting to trump’s intended trans’ rights grab don’t know intersex kids get bits literally cut off/out our bodies to fit us in ridiculous pink & blue boxes!! thank you lilly singh @iisuperwomanii & @tildacanyouhearme for casting me in your next holiday season #iisuperwomanii @youtube vid. we shot yesterday & i can’t wait for people to see it! the scripts 😂🤣😂 the part is so perfect for me.. and answers why i’m here in #hollywood & not with my family in 🇬🇧 getting ready for the holidays. and am working with @gaptoofentertainment to build #newhollywood from the #metoo , racist, sexist, ashes. *just exec produced @ponyboi_film 🌎 1st #intersexy movie. ps i feel better now- happy holliday’s😁

text: wanna know what floats my boat? mentoring creative talent. our sponsorship of fashion week san diego provides the ultimate venue to do just that with the opening night, the art and beauty behind fashion. this year our stylists teamed up with a designer and makeup artist to create a complete look inspired by paintings supplied by the art renewal center and artists from around the world. the event was hosted here in encinitas at the lux art institute. here my stylists roberta, katrina and ashley created a textured and braided style for janne robinson's painting titled "me too". the style speaks to contrived constructs of feminine beauty, with details that, though noticeable, still fit within for an image of unoffended and graceful fluidity. photo by @656photography

text:
instagram ijtimoiy tarmog‘i xodimlari foydalanuvchilar tomonidan qo‘yilgan smayliklar, geolokatsiya va xeshteglarni tahlil qilishdi hamda 2018 yil yakunlari haqida ma'lumot berishdi. bu haqda instagram rasmiy saytida xabar qilingan.

shu tariqa, eng baxtli geolokatsiya sifatida instagram tokiodagi disneylendni tan oldi, sababi 2018 yilda eng baxtli smayliklar foydalanuvchilar tomonidan aynan yaponiyadagi disneylenddan olingan suratlar ostiga qo‘yilgan.

shuningdek, ekspertlar yuz uchun eng ommabop filtrni ma'lum qilishdi: unga ko‘zlarida yurakchalar bo‘lgan filtr aylandi. bundan tashqari, 2018 yilda eng ko‘p ishlatilgan xeshteglar #metoo, #timesup va #marchforourlives bo‘ldi.

noyabr oyida which? britaniya iste'molchilar assotsiatsiyasi xodimlari sayohat qilish uchun eng xavfsiz davlatlar reytingini tuzishdi. mutaxassislar to‘rtta mezon bo‘yicha 20ta eng ommabop turistik yo‘nalishni tahlil qilib chiqishgan: jinoyatchilik darajasi, sog‘liqqa tahdid, terakt ehtimoli va tabiiy ofatlar. barcha mezonlar bo‘yicha eng xavfsiz mamlakatga islandiya aylandi.

this one was mainly inspired by the #metoo movement. and the call-out of men and women across the world, victims of sexual harassment.

here is an overview of the creative process behind it:

the main piece takes the shape of a pyramid of perverts, forming an allegorical hierarchy of persecution. 
from the petty fondlers and harassers, at the bottom. to the devious and manipulative big shots, at the top. 
some trying to accaparate the woman for themselves. some united together, in a sinister effort to humiliate her. 
all in a flurry of overwhelmingly libidinous power, towards what they obviously consider a mere sexual object.

regarding the circle of characters surrounding it. it is both a metaphorical representation of us as a society, and a recursion, of an hypothetical audience, attending the installation, from their own point of view. 
all of them trying to turn a blind eye on the direct issue, or rather threat, that they are experiencing.
in a vain attempt to coward away from the scene, they only find themselves hopeless, in front of a mirror.
constrained to watch the tragedy, but also contemplate their own reflection.

as a final word. i would like to clarify, that this is an issue i have only been exterior of. 
this is not me, speaking in the name of oppressed women. but rather my own harsh perspective as a man. based on observation towards beings of my own gender.
#videoedits #metoo #metoomovement #edits #edits #animation

text:
december 13 maybe just a normal day like other days. it is the 81 years anniversary of the nanjing massacre, or rape of nanjing. it was an episode of mass murder and rape committed by japanese troops against the residents of nan jing, then the capital of china, during the second sino-japanese war. 
i read a story of a comfort woman-tatoo and i will never forget it. the true story is disturbing💔it reveals some truths about what happened in the past and how it continued to impact the person for the rest of their lives. there are many chinese and korean women are forced to be “comfort women” during that time. this made me sad, angry and powerless. 
according to china comfort women issue research center, only 6 comfort women had survived in china by 2018. when the number becomes 0, will this part of history also be forgotten? it took many years for people to admit this massacre really happened.this has always caused tension between china and japan. 
those events are on my textbooks and i learn about them from my history class. we have ceremonies to remember those who lost their lives during a time without humanity. the past make who we are now, a country’s past is part of its stories today. 
it is hard to talk about history and politics especially if you are not the person who are impacted directly, who cares what happened so many years ago? 
however, if we don’t care, we don’t admit the mistakes that have been made by our ancestors, the history will repeat itself again. 
here are some facts:

the massacre occurred over a period of six weeks starting on december 13, 1937.

since most japanese military records on the killings were kept secret or destroyed shortly after the surrender of japan in 1945, historians have been unable to accurately estimate the death toll of the massacre. china's official estimate is more than 300,000 dead.

for full story about the comfort woman, click this link:
http://foxtalk.tistory.com/m/98

text:
"respect yourself by respecting others." -miya yamanouchi , embrace your sexual self: a practical guide for women (2015)

i have a topic i would like to share, and it is something i feel strongly about.
did you know 77% of woman exp verbal sexual harassment at some point in their life, in men its 34%, and even then some more in both probably.
(i am not setting aside physical assault either those statistics are just as validated im just isolating this issue specifically.)
i myself come from a long history of sexual abuse growing up, and one sexually violent relationship. 
did you know to that people often don't see the signs weither its socially or even in the workplace to???
i mean how can you prepare yourself to exp being the victim or seeing it happen anyways? even with training, being taught growing up etc.
the best thing you can do is if you see someone is confused/uncomfortable, or asking for it to stop is to step in and help...even if you are uncomfortable.
some people even take it as, "they were just joking." and thats even more sad.
i had the lovely exp with this this past week, even though my man stuck up for me twice, i ended up having to put my foot down in the end (and behave in a way i normally don't act to get my point acrossed that i will be respected, and it is disgusting.)
and of course said person retaliated...which is very common to btw.
the situation has been taken care of! minus some panic attacks later i am ok, but still abit on edge. even though i have moved on from parts of my pasts they still have nasty side effects every blue moon...and it sucks but you can't control other peoples nastieness, but how you react and take action is what is important!
don't keep quiet about unwanted sexual remarks, or assault. its not fricken cool, and i am glad i have strong bones to not tolerate being pushed around like bait.
this is a call for all woman to be strong and feirce. your a rose garden with thorns, not dirt under someones fingernails.
#metoo #notcool #dontkeepquiet #sexualharassmentawareness  #speakout #helpeachother #bestrong #bebrave #becourageous #empowerwoman #tourvoicematters

f i v e // ways to get money matters in order #advocate #idaho——————————————————————
as you prepare to leave your abuser, make sure you know where your money is.
when you begin planning to leave your abusive partner, money will likely be a major concern. your partner might be financially abusing you by controlling the household finances, not allowing you to work, or forcing you to work and taking your money, or using your credit.
it might seem daunting, but there are ways you can keep your assets safe and accessible in the future. everything from bank accounts, retirement funds, insurance and investments to your credit cards, property, and vehicles should be considered, if there is time, before you make the final move to separate. suffice it to say, the step should only be taken if it’s safe to do so, that’s is, if you can do them without raising the suspicion of your abuser or putting yourself in added danger. —————————————————————— #lifestyle #family #loveshouldnthurt #december #enddv #byui #dvfacts #dancing #entrepreneur #fall #design #wellness #marketing #friends #idaho #timesup #metoo #idaho #health #breakthesilence #idaho #graphicdesign #healthy #winter

text:
instagram ижтимоий тармоғи ходимлари фойдаланувчилар томонидан қўйилган смайликлар, геолокация ва хештегларни таҳлил қилишди ҳамда 2018 йил якунлари ҳақида маълумот беришди. бу ҳақда instagram расмий сайтида хабар қилинган.

шу тариқа, энг бахтли геолокация сифатида instagram токиодаги диснейлендни тан олди, сабаби 2018 йилда энг бахтли смайликлар фойдаланувчилар томонидан айнан япониядаги диснейленддан олинган суратлар остига қўйилган.

шунингдек, экспертлар юз учун энг оммабоп фильтрни маълум қилишди: унга кўзларида юракчалар бўлган фильтр айланди. бундан ташқари, 2018 йилда энг кўп ишлатилган хештеглар #metoo, #timesup ва #marchforourlives бўлди.

ноябрь ойида which? британия истеъмолчилар ассоциацияси ходимлари саёҳат қилиш учун энг хавфсиз давлатлар рейтингини тузишди. мутахассислар тўртта мезон бўйича 20та энг оммабоп туристик йўналишни таҳлил қилиб чиқишган: жиноятчилик даражаси, соғлиққа таҳдид, теракт эҳтимоли ва табиий офатлар. барча мезонлар бўйича энг хавфсиз мамлакатга исландия айланди.

text:
i know the incredible energy and willpower it takes for survivors to go to work, school, run errands, take care of siblings and kids, maintain friendships and relationships, and all while struggling with the aftermath of sexual abuse. trying to function through the day-to-day can drain even the most willful survivor’s energy. the purpose of this resource library is to give survivors the tools and resources they need to practice the self-care that will get them through the aftermath of sexual abuse. if you can, please consider donating to this resource library at patreon.com/roarmvmt (link in bio)

text:
why i wrote angels in the or:  what dying taught me about healing, survival and transformation: part ii (available in may 2019)

i wrote this book for so many darn reasons.  1) yes, near-death experiences should be a deeper part of the cultural consciousness. we need a variety of speakers talking about afterlife experiences. those of us without a fear of death can bring much comfort to people. 2) spiritual phenomenon such as angel guidance and mediumship can be a greater part or our cultural conversations. the other side offers us all great healing directly.  3) i also wrote this book because i was a young woman who experienced sexual assault in a foreign country. those of us who have survived sexual trauma and worked deeply on healing trauma can push national and global conversations about this subject to help enact real changes in how women are treated in court systems around the globe.  it isn’t “focusing on the negative” when you are actively working to make this world a safer place for others. 4) i wrote this book because teaching was my mission from god. good teachers need more recognition for all the work they do to help others.  5) i wrote this book because i hate the adage, “those who can’t do, teach.” oh…...whatever.  i have over twenty-five years in education, and i am so excited about my publisher and book cover. i used george orwell, frank mccourt, and steven king as inspiration.  they all taught school for many years, but they also proved that they could both teach and do!  i beat the odds to inspire my students to keep beating odds. 6) i wrote this book because i had the support of god, my ancestors (especially my dad and grandfather) and so many amazing spiritual supporters along the way. louise hay, david foster wallace, and robin williams showed up in spirit to encourage me at different times. this journey has been magical 💫 every journey is!!
.
#highervibes #higherawakening #davidfosterwallace #higherconsciousness #teachers #stephenking #georgeorwell #frankmccourt #metoo #metooamerica #metoomovement #metoo❤️ #memoir #memoirs #memoirsaturdays #memoirwriting #newbook #angelsintheor #healer #healingjourney #healingenergy #womensupportingwomen

text_retweet:
repost @joydemente with @get_repost
・・・
hace un día, subí un vídeo  donde una joven declara que cuando tenia 16  un actor de 45, abusó sexualmente de ella. 
antes de ella, varias personas habían denunciado al mismo actor. 
para los que me siguen desde hace un tiempo, saben que el año pasado junto a la autora del libro @seterminaconmigo hicimos live  sobre las distintas formas de abuso: verbal, fisica, sexual y psicológica. hablamos incluso de los movimientos #metoo con el acoso. 
en esa etapa, entrevistamos a muchas personas. una fue jose benegas analista político que años después contó que había sido abusado por su hermano. 
otra, fue ines hercovich,  socióloga y psicóloga social argentina con una amplia trayectoria investigando temas con las diferentes formas de discriminación de la mujer. 
ines dijo 2 cosas claves.” 1: como sociedad, “ le subimos el volumen a las cosas que decidimos escuchar”’como por ejemplo: ¿quien la manda a ir a esos boliches. los mini, los escote? son juicios que terminan en una sentencia :“ella se la buscó.” “si se la buscó también  consintió”.
lo peor de todo, es que las mujeres son, quien en su mayoría, toman esta postura. 
deciden culpabilizar a las víctimas 
la 2da cosa , es que sociedad tiene un papel vital en que estas cosas dejen de pasar. ¿cómo? pues aprendiendo a creer en la víctima.

muchas personas se preguntan por qué lo dicen años más tarde. yo nunca sufrí un tipo de abuso, pero sufrí la muerte prematura de mi mamá y la pude poner en palabra ( aun siendo psicólogo) 15 años más tarde. ¿entonces es mentira que mi mamá murió? 
una de las cosas más difíciles que hay es “poder poner en palabra cosas traumáticas” eso implica aceptarlo, asimilarlo, tener confianza ¿y como se tiene confianza en una sociedad que decide no creer? 
comentarios como : “ahora a todas las violaron y todas hablaron” si. eso sucede. si alguien se anima a contar su historia los demás lo pueden hacer. 
en venezuela hubo un caso de un psiquiatra quien había violado a sus pacientes y la última chica, que el violó y asesinó hizo, que encontraran más de 2000 fotos de mujeres violadas y . el cambio comienza por nosotros. #miracomonosponemos #psicologia #abuso #

text:
do you see yourself as amazing and strong?

personally i'm one of the strongest people i know. i dont intend to toot my own horn, but i've been to hell and back more than once. and i've made the choice to get back up, after many falls. most of the time this has been painfully hard.

i choose to celebrate my victories whether big or small. to focus on my positives rather than feed the negatives.

are you your own hero? do you realize how far you have come?

still a queen 👑✊.
.
.
.

text:
if there is anything i’ve learned in this season, it is that being a truth-teller is not being divisive.

speaking the truth is only destruction to those that are content right where they’re at. truth is freedom. bringing light to a situation is not gossip. it is unifying. well, it should be.

there are more people that want to shut you up than listen to you. that’s real. contentment in wondering, assuming and gossip rather than listening and seeking to understand is a way of life for many.

speak. the. truth.

i’m praying for a generation to say, “you know what?...that’s not right. we swept that under the rug, and it was wrong. let’s listen, love, and change.” my truth and what i can’t get off my mind right now is i’ve experienced and seen ladies that love jesus, have leadership skills, are talented and experienced yet still are overlooked by the “church” for employment....using one verse to justify.

it’s me. it’s a friend. it’s a mentor. it’s a instafriend. it’s every woman in the south i’ve encountered trying to make a living in the house of worship.
i’ve had enough.

jesus lifted the heads of women and poured his spirit out on men and women. my “role” in that is to walk in that. tradition can go move on....let the truth walk in.

i could tell you story after story of my own and others that are told that they will be paid less and receive less respect because of their gender...within the working context of the church.

my father sees this...and he tells me “go get it. i made you to declare my truth”. my father in heaven and my father on earth never held me back, and i will never hold my future daughter back.if she has fire in her bones, how dare i hold her back.

i’ll tell her...”speak the truth even if your voice shakes.” i’m rooting for you, women. i’m rooting for the men that want to team up and not push down. bless those men, they’re not scared.

my voice is shaking, but i’ll keep talking if you need to.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company “weaponised” the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how users’ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms – facebook, in particular – were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaign’s lesser reported “weapons of mass destruction”. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someone’s personality. a user’s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call “populist political signalling”. cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump’s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 – including cultural preferences such as fashion and music – to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

tweet_full:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company “weaponised” the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how users’ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms – facebook, in particular – were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaign’s lesser reported “weapons of mass destruction”. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someone’s personality. a user’s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call “populist political signalling”. cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump’s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 – including cultural preferences such as fashion and music – to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
this is for every man, woman and child who has a phone or computer. contact tennessee gov bill haslam to grant cyntoia brown clemency. ph: 615-741-2001 email: bill.haslam@tn.gov •

she’s not the only one who needs our help but she’s the one we can help right now. you are one person. an individual. we are a population. a movement. our singular actions are impactful as we realize the bigger picture. please make your voice heard and fight for this child who has more than earned the right for freedom. • ***warning: this may be triggering***
i’ve stayed silent for years. even through the #metoo movement. the stories of pain and triumph were covering the news and i was frozen. stuck in fear and shame for not speaking up. for not calling out the man who hurt me “soon enough”. for not immediately going to the hospital to have a rape kit done but instead showering and trying to scrub off the last 24 hrs of hellish memories, my shame, my own skin. trying to erase the trauma, fully knowing that i was washing away any evidence that could help my case should i take him to court. i spent the next year debating the length of my life. the day i chose survival, i chose just that; to survive. i never realized there was more until recently. thriving is what we can do. that’s our choice in life. we can allow ourselves to have passions and joy and to live above fear and shame and pride because we’re the only ones who can suppress our inner-selves. •

survival is what cyntoia fought for and won. the freedom to choose how she lives her life is what you can fight for. •

here is my request: please don’t like this post or comment. instead, spend the 1-2 minutes you would take on a comment or take a fraction of the next 30 minutes you’d probably spend scrolling through this app and type an email to bill haslam. do it for cyntoia. she needs your thoughts and actions most right now.

episode #2 of the now age podcast features jesse carlota heid of @alignedspirit and is one of the deepest, most impactful conversations about healing i have had this year. a former habitual psychedelics user, and now 10 years sober, jesse shares her story of successfully self-medicating from the chronic pain that has been the fallout of her childhood abuse with powerful and raw honesty and vulnerability. more than a survivor, jesse is thriving as a result of all she learned about healing, about self-love, and about our connection to spirit, during her “psychedelic years,” and her insight into both the emotional root of chronic dis-ease, how our bodies really heal, and the legacy of colonization, is utterly compelling. i urge you to listen to her story and i defy you not to be deeply, deeply moved. link to listen is in my profile 💜 #newmotherline #endometriosis  #cptsd #ptsd #psychedelics #nowagepodcast #alignedspirit #depthpsychology #storymedicine #autoimmunedisease #chronicillness #chronicpain #cannabis #metoo #divinemother #spoonie #woundedhealer #vulnerabilityhangover

text_retweet:
had a great chat with the very fun @tamwrigley_official - and she brought wine. very polite.
you can check it out at the @thewineoclockshow site 🍷🍷🍷🍷🍷
#repost @thewineoclockshow
・・・
happy friday peeps!
.
and more importantly, happy #wineoclock time.  you know what that means, yeap, it's time for this weeks episdoe of the wine o'clock show and this week we chat with one of australia's most versatile and much loved entertainers. from leading tv roles on home and away, house husbands, big sky, dead gorgeous and host of national prime time shows celebrity singing bee, wheel of fortune, national bingo night and countless other tv programs, to lead roles in the stage shows wicked, rent and shout! he is certainly a star of both stage and screen.
.
when he’s not dancing with the stars, he is entertaining on channel 9’s carols by candlelight.  that's right, @timcampbelltwit is on the couch.
.
this week is all about christmas as tim celebrates 10 years of singing at @channel9 's carols by candlelight. tim has performed at venues all over the australia, been on hit tv show, smash hit theatre productions, so we find out why the channel 9 carols by candlelight event unique.  what’s been the highlight of performing at the carols over the last 10 years and what’s been his favourite song to deliver?
.
we also chat about the big christmas tree debate - in what order do you decorate? is it lights, tinsel, balls and decorations?
.
tim also give's his opinion on whether the 74 year old christmas classic “baby it’s cold outside” be removed from our radio stations after an ohio radio station has stopped playing a classic 74-year-old christmas song because it offends proponents of the increasingly criticized #metoo movement.
.
tim also released a new album this year called electrifying 80’s, our favourite era, we find out which amazing 80's classic's made the album and why.
.
all this a so much more, this week on the wine o'clock show. link in bio
.

text:
morgan spurlock settles suit over unproduced tnt docuseries, will pay turner nets $1.18m
##metoo #breaking news #legal #morgan spurlock #tnt #turner entertainment networks #warrior poets #who rules the world
oscar- and emmy-nominated documentarian morgan spurlock has agreed to pay more than $1.17 million to turner entertainment networks to settle a lawsuit over a female-focused docuseries he ended up not making. the project was shelved after he posted a confessional essay as the #metoo movement was gaining strength. the settlement (read it here) ends turner’s lawsuit over the planned tnt docuseries who rules the world, whose logline says was to be about the most divisive and complicated issues facing women today, from the policing of their bodies and judgments of their family planning choices to the micro-aggressions they face in the media, the workplace and everyday life. shutterstock production on the project was suspended a year ago after its producers severed ties with spurlock. that move came days after the super size me filmmaker posted a lengthy manifesto in which he admitted to being “part of the problem” as sexual harassment allegations were exploding all over hollywood. in his post spurlock gave his thoughts on sexual harassment and how heroes had fallen for their indiscretions, asking, “when will they come for me?” fallout was swift and merciless as youtube pulled out of funding spurlock’s super size me 2 and sundance dropped the docu sequel from its 2018 lineup. showtime then dropped his park city-bound docuseries the trade, which focused on the opioid crisis. spurlock that week also stepped down from his production company warrior poets, which also was defendant in the lawsuit turner filed in late march, when the project still was in its early stages.

text:
#otd in 1918 women voted for the first time in a uk general election.

but things were far from being equal: they had to have some wealth and to be over 30 years old to qualify.
there were fears they would out-vote men due to the deaths of wwi which had finished only a month before.

ten years later, in 1928, women were finally given the right to vote on equal terms with men by the equal franchise act.

visit the @museumoflondon to learn more about the suffragettes and their invaluable fight for women's rights.

pictured, a statue of emmeline pankhurst outside the houses of parliament and 
the museum's collab with @tattydevine

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
“over a year ago, the #metoo movement exploded into the public eye, causing the downfall of multiple powerful men in hollywood. while some remained unscathed, 201 prominent men have since lost their positions of power.
•
as a brown guy, this movement has prompted me to think about something i’ve never consciously considered: what it means to be an ally for women. factually, i know what the patriarchy is. i know what male privilege looks like. but like many of my ‘woke’ peers, i’ve thought of myself as one of the ‘nice guys.’ i treat my colleagues and peers with respect. i never make lewd comments. i’m respectful of people’s boundaries. from my perspective, i’ve crossed my t’s and dotted my i’s.”— @virenshinde_
•
this and more, click on the link in our bio to read how to be an ally to the women in your life! ⬆️👩🏽
•
📸 @shalommwenesi
•

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. he’s the only straight man i’ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
‘pyjamas are forgiving’ by @twinklerkhanna. published by @juggernaut.in (2018).
•
if i hadn’t read a review of this book in @elleindia i would have judged it by its cover & never picked it up in @bahrisons_booksellers. despite thinking it might be a frothy jilly cooper-esque novel set in a south indian wellness resort (new genre alert?) i was pleasantly surprised & genuinely loved this book & was very sad to finish it. the story centres around anshu, a divorcee in her mid-forties returning for her biannual cleanse at shanthamaaya sthalam wellness retreat. however this year her stay is disturbed by the unexpected arrival of her ex-husband & his new (much younger) wife. this could have been just a good account of the difficulties of a failed relationship & the allure & nostalgia of the past, but the novel slowly unravelled to become so much more than that. khanna’s skill is to weave issues in the forefront of contemporary indian social life (homosexuality, islamophobia, gender-based violence & the #metoo movement) into a gentle novel set in the supposedly safe boundaries of a retreat in green, lush & rainy kerala.
•
will appeal to those who have spent extended time at indian wellness retreats (wearing white pyjamas all day long) 🙏🏼

text:
あのね、たとえ寂しくても、全ての人類を受け入れる必要はないよ。
この人には会いたいけど、この人はダメとか、個人単位で選り好みしていい。それは別に贅沢じゃない。
あと、時々の気分でそれが、変わってもいい。みんなそうだから。

even if you are lonely, you do not have to accept all humanity. we'd like to meet this person, but this person is ok, we can choose it by per individual. it's not extravagant.
also, it can change with the mood sometimes. because everyone is so.

#metoo #remetoo #praisethebrave #bubbleoff

text:
beth moore was a featured speaker at a one-day summit on sexual abuse and harassment thursday at wheaton college in suburban chicago — and one of many who described their own experiences of abuse and harassment.

some shared their stories of sexual abuse for the first time, including bestselling christian author and pastor max lucado and child advocate kelly rosati.

read more about the summit and what organizers hoped it would accomplish in my report for @religionnews. #linkinbio #metoo #churchtoo #religion #journalism #journalismlife

・・・
i will always tell, and have always told, the truth. even when my voice shakes.
•
you asking “why now” simply reveals to me that you haven’t been paying attention. “journalists” who distort the words of women to produce clickbait, who minimize their story by segmenting it and reducing it?  do better.
•
if you have chosen not to listen to the frank, clear conversations i’ve had on the topic over the last year, that’s on you. your lack of attention — to me and to all of the women who tell their stories into the void — doesn’t mean that we haven’t been screaming all along.
•
to attempt to have a field day with my life, acting like i don’t have the receipts? *you can swipe right for a selection.
•
the grace with which i’ve chosen to handle this, the deep learning i’ve done in the wake of my experience (shout out to the magnificent folks at @onsiteworkshops) that i take as sacred, and a responsibility to offer other women? do not forget that my “titanium spine,” as my sister @hilarieburton calls it, was forged in fire. i am not a woman that you will ever reduce. not one iota. none of us are. #doyougetitnow #metoo #burnitdown #timesup poem: @nayyirah.waheed

tw: rape, ipv
i don’t know how to start this essay. i cried out all my words yesterday, but i they are replenishing now. i wrung out my pain and now they are black icicles dripping from my extremities. 
so, i will start with the fundamentals. a man raped me. this is not a new phenomenon in the world and it is not a new phenomenon in my life. a decade ago, in high school, i had a boyfriend who would viciously torture and rape me. i have to turn my soul to stone to write those words. he fit the textbook definition of a narcissistic manipulator. he became a marine. he has a child now. he’s getting his mba now. i’m still afraid of him now. i never reported him because he made my life hell. i thought he would kill me and my family. he was capable of it. perhaps the biggest miracle of my life is when he broke up with me inexplicably on easter sunday. i want to frame it as some sort of symbolic resurrection, but i just can’t.  maybe this is a narrow view of resurrection, or the tendency of the white evangelical christian church to cast resurrection as all clouds and glory, not the nitty gritty of scars and healing.

anyway. 
i carried those scars for a decade, though they mostly faded. in august, they ripped open and multiplied. another man raped and stalked me. i met him at a mutual friend’s party in the winter, but we didn’t talk at all past that night until we matched on tinder in the summer. he raped me in my home, in my bed. he remains convinced he did no wrong. i remain shattered. i reported the rape, beginning the arduous, still ongoing investigation and legal process. it is a secondary hell. 
i am on the verge of dropping out of school. i started taking medication for my severe depression, ptsd, and suicidality. most days i can barely eat or leave my house, let alone research complex scientific concepts.
just as i didn’t know how to start this essay, i don’t know how to end it. -anonymous 
#metoo
#25daysofsweaters

text: the artist’s current exhibition, “will she ever shut up?,” at ppow, her second at the new york gallery, is about what came next—and not just in the studio. the rise of the #metoo movement, unleashed after the long-overdue condemnation of hollywood director and serial abuser harvey weinstein, figures prominently in the show. now the artist’s work is filled not only with words about women, but also with the labored apologies issued by various men brought low by allegations of sexual misconduct.- interview with sarah cascone with betty tompkins @artnet @bettytompkinsart @sarahecascone 💓

text:
#psychotherapy is one of many ways of healing trauma
.
for most women it requires a combination of psychotherapy, nutrition, supplements, biofeedback, good sleep, meditation, yoga, martial arts, nature, spirituality/religion, medication, energy healing (e.g. reiki), massages, work-life balance, community involvement, support of family/friends, self-help books/blogs/podcasts, and the list goes on and on!  you can start anywhere and allow your intuition to guide you...one step at a time...
healing trauma is a journey...a work-in-progress! .
👉🏼 visit my website to learn more about trauma-focused treatment
.
.
